There is a specimen (SAM K1369) that I have examined and that Joshua and Creed 1915 mis-identified as Cucumaria squamata Ludwig, 1898 (Kerguelen species ... a Trachythyone).  H. L. Clark 1946 proposed the replacement name Cucumaria squamatoides.  A. M. Clark 1966 (p. 345) pointed out that the specimen was never adequately described by Joshua and Creed nor examined by H. L. Clark, and therefore did not satisfy the ICZN.  Hence her nomen nudum. column36: "A specimen collected off Western Australia by Mjoberg was seemingly fully described and figured and identified as Cucumaria japonica Semper, 1868 (p. 236) by Ekman 1918.  H. L. Clark 1946 was advised by Deichmann (pers comm) and judged that the specimen could not be C. japonica, and erected the species Cucumaria adela H. L. Clark, 1946.  Rowe and Gates 1995 anticipated that the specimen and thus holotype is in the Naturhistoriske Riksmuseum in Stockholm.  It appears then that there is a good description (Ekman) and a type specimen (Stockholm) and I assume that the species is thus valid unless it is shown that Ekman was correct in his determination (not impossible!) and adela would thus be a junior synonym of japonica.  I have not been into the rules about this issue but I assume that there is no demand that the author has examined the type on which the new taxon is based?  If this is a condition then adela would be a nomen nudum." MOL in litt. IX.2010

column36: Pawson, David wrote, On 9/20/2010 9:15 AM: Siphothuria incurvata was first mentioned by E. Perrier (1886), with an illustration (was this a description???).  Then in 1902 R. Perrier described Cucumaria incurvata nov.sp., listing under this n.sp. name two literature citations:  R. Perrier 1898 Comptes Rendus CXXV! P. 1665, and R. Perrier 1899 Bull Mus. D'Hist. Nat Paris V, p. 300.  Also listed in R. Perrier 1902 as a synonym (!) of Cucumaria incurvata nov. sp. is:  "Syn.: Siphothuria incurvata, E. Perrier Les Expl. sous-marines 1886, p.286, fig. 202. So, four references to the species incurvata, and which one can be taken as the valid description, etc???  The bloody Perrier boys did this many times, as you probably know. Then, in discussing Cucumaria tergestina Sars, 1857, Koehier (1927) Les Echinodermes des mers d'Europe lists "C. incurvata" as a junior synonym.  So that's where it sits today, although tergestina is known today, apparently, as Leptopentacta tergestina (M. sars, 1857).
